data.name: AMPK
data.value: The AMPK enzyme is the master metabolic switch in each of your cells. When AMPK levels increase you get an energy boost, blood glucose is regulated, insulin sensitivity improves, reduced triglycerides, and increased fat-burning in mitochondria. The metabolism of the whole organism becomes considerably more efficient

data.name: Antioxidant
data.value: A substance that is able to protect the body from oxidaitve stress (from free radicals) either by neutralising the radical or by protecting tissues, or both.

data.name: Anxiolytic
data.value: Reduces anxiety

data.name: BloodBrainBarrier
data.value: The blood–brain barrier protects against circulating toxins or pathogens that could cause brain infections, while at the same time allowing vital nutrients to reach the brain.

data.name: Cortisol
data.value: The major stress hormone of the body. In excess, cortisol can result int he breakdown of tissues, resulting in degenerative disease.

data.name: CReactiveProtein
data.value: CRP is a protein secreted mostly by cells in the liver in response to a variety of inflammatory cytokines. CRP plays important roles in inflammatory processes including by altering pathways involved in apoptosis, phagocytosis, nitric oxide release and production of cytokines. Elevated CRP is a reliable marker of chronic inflammation.

data.name: FreeRadicals
data.value: Free radicals result from oxidation in cells and damage tissues in the body. They are implicated in many types of age-related diseases.

data.name: HumanGrowthHormone
data.value: Peptide hormone that stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and cell regeneration in humans and other animals. It is thus important in human development. GH also stimulates production of IGF-1 and increases the concentration of glucose and free fatty acids.

data.name: Mitochondria
data.value: The organelles of cells responsible for producing all of our ATP (cellular energy)

data.name: Mitochondrial
data.value: Relating to the 'mitochondria':the organelles of cells responsible for producing all of our ATP (cellular energy)

data.name: Mitochondriogenesis
data.value: Stimulates the growth of new mitochondria and the repair of existing ones.

data.name: NAD
data.value: NAD+ mediates the production of the energy our cells need to function and survive, fueling enzymes key in repairing DNA damage. As we age, this indispensable molecule progressively declines.

data.name: Neurogenesis
data.value: The generation of new neurons

data.name: Neuromelanins
data.value: Pigments that form in the brain that are similar to the melanin pigment in the skin.

data.name: Nootropic
data.value: Nootropics can help to improve memory, boost learning ability, enhance mood and assist overall brain function and health.

data.name: OxidativeStress
data.value: Damage to tissues and cells caused by free radicals, which is implicated in many chronic, degenerative diseases.

data.name: ATP
data.value: Adenosine triphosphate, also known as ATP, is a molecule that carries energy within cells. It is the main energy currency of the cell.

data.name: BDNF
data.value: A potent neurotrophin that stimulates the genesis of new neurons in the brain is referred to as neurogenesis. BDNF is implicated in neuroplasticity, learning, memory and higher thinking.

data.name: CBSMutation
data.value: A genetic SNP or polymorphism (i.e. variant), which predisposes certain individual's to difficulties processing and detoxifying certain environmental chemicals as well as making them more susceptible to stress.

data.name: Dopamine
data.value: A major neurotransmitter of the catecholamine family, implicated in pleasure, focus, motivation, memory, movement, mood, blood vessel function, planning and more.

data.name: GABA
data.value: GABA is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter produced in the body. It helps to countr excessive neural excitement. GABA is implicated in mood, sleep, stress, anxiety, speech, cognition, memory, focus, blood pressure and more.

data.name: Glutamate
data.value: GABA is the main excitatory neurotransmitter produced in the body. It excites neurons and is implicated in memory, concentration, mood, cellular energy production, neuroplasticity and the growth and development of the brain.

data.name: Homocysteine
data.value: Homocysteine is a specific type of amino acid that’s created in the body during metabolic processes, as opposed to consumed in food. It’s produced in the body as a byproduct of methylation. Excessive homocysteine is often observed in chronic inflammatory diseases.

data.name: Methylation
data.value: The act of giving a methyl group to another compound altering its chemical structure thereby changing it to something else. This is a carefully orchestrated transfer from one compound to another which requires an enzymatic process. Methylation is an essential and major part of our metabolism and any imbalances in methylation produce varying degrees of pathology.

data.name: MethylGroup
data.value: A substance that is capable of donating a methyl group to another compound.

data.name: Neuroplasticity
data.value: Neuroplasticity or brain plasticity is the inherent ability of the brain to adapt and change in reaction to internal and external stimuli. Your brain can change its functions and even its physical structure to react to inputs coming in from events, experiences, thoughts, and even human emotions.

data.name: Neurotransmitter
data.value: A chemical messenger used by the nervous system to send messages between nerve cells.

data.name: NitricOxide
data.value: Nitric oxide is a key molecule in the cardiovascular system that helps keep blood vessels healthy and regulates blood pressure.

data.name: NMDA
data.value:
NMDA receptor is a type of G protein-coupled ionotropic glutamate receptor that plays a crucial role in regulating a wide variety of neurological functions, including breathing, locomotion, learning, memory formation, and neuroplasticity.
Accordingly, structural and functional impairment of the NMDA receptor can lead to neurodegenerative and cognitive disorders, including Alzheimer’s disease, Parkinson’s disease, Huntington disease, neuropathic pain, epilepsy, and psychiatric disorders.

data.name: Norepinephrine
data.value: A major neurotransmitter of the catecholamine family, implicated in focus, blood pressure, mood, sleep healthy stress response and more.

data.name: Serotonin
data.value: A neurotransmitter that plays a role in sleep, appetite, learning, memory, mood, sexual function and more.

data.name: Teolmerase
data.value:
Telomerase is an enzyme found inside our cells, which may be related to the aging process. It adds short, repetitive "caps" to our DNA strands. These caps are called "telomeres."
Each time our cells divide, they must replicate their DNA so that each daughter cell gets a full set of operating instructions. However, with each cell division, a small part of the DNA strand’s protective telomeres are lost.
Scientists believe that the loss of telomeres leads to eventual loss of important, coding regions of DNA, and that this impairs cells’ ability to divide and produce healthy daughter cells over time.
